I don't think using comments is a good short-term workaround:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>      &lt;!-- content --&gt;<br />         A part dealing with the page's topic<br />      &lt;!-- /content --&gt;</code></dd></dl>Authors already tend to identify the &quot;real content&quot; of their page via <a href="http://code.google.com/webstats/2005-12/classes.html" class="postlink">the use of <span style="font-weight: bold">class</span> names</a>, presumably like this:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>      &lt;div class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;<br />         A part dealing with the page's topic<br />      &lt;/div&gt;</code></dd></dl>I often see this:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>      &lt;div id=&quot;content&quot;&gt;<br />         A part dealing with the page's topic<br />      &lt;/div&gt;</code></dd></dl>So I think identifying multiple blocks with <span style="font-weight: bold">class=&quot;content&quot;</span> or just a single block with <span style="font-weight: bold">id=&quot;content&quot;</span> puts you more in line with the web as it currently stands.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=27">Cerbera</a> — Sat Apr 28, 2007 12:34 pm</p><hr />
